{
  "doc_id": "prion_0548",
  "text": "We report the case history of a 54-year-old man who developed a fatal neurological disorder 4 years after a successful tympanoplasty with homograft pericardium.\nThe final diagnosis of this case was Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease.\nThis infectious spongiform encephalopathy is probably caused by a slow virus that can be transmitted by transplantation materials.\nThe possible accidental transmission of Creutzfeldt-Jacob disease by the use of homograft materials in otologic surgery is discussed.",
